REMINDER: tomorrow, Thursday, August 27th is the final pick-up day for the USDA summer feeding program. Four days’ worth of breakfast and lunch are available for pickup to anyone 18 years old and younger from 10am-noon at C.R. Weeks Elementary and A.F Palmer Elementary/Windsor Central Middle School.

The Windsor Central School District will begin its free breakfast and lunch program on the first day of school. Lunches for on-site and hybrid-model students start September 10th. Students choosing 100 percent remote can pick up their first week of meals on Sept 9th.

post_text: Girls Who Code at Binghamton University is offering an online computer science program for high school level girls in the Southern Tier of New York. The club strives to give young girls interested in STEM the support needed to shape them into future CEOs and strong women in the workforce. In a matter of weeks, these young women who have little to no experience in coding will learn various programming languages, build creative projects to better their community, and join a sisterhood of supportive peers.

post_text:
With voters approving the 2020-21 Windsor Central School District budget and the New York State Department of Health releasing guidance in regard to day camps, the District has begun planning and preparation for summer programming.

Please be aware that as a result of COVID-19, camp offerings will be fewer and shorter in duration this summer. Additionally, all camps will be outdoors, weather-dependent, and, as a result of the strict guidance regarding buses, transportation will not be provided.

Despite the changes and health regulations, these camps will still be a great opportunity to get kids active, engaged and reconnecting with friends in the great outdoors over the summer.

More information regarding summer camp opportunities will be available within the next two weeks.

To read more about the NYS DOH day camp health and safety guidelines, please click: https://ocfs.ny.gov/main/news/2020/COVID-2020Jun08-Day-Camp-Summary.pdf

post_text:
There are still scholarship opportunities open for new SUNY Broome students! And, even better news — the deadline has just been *extended* to Friday, June 12th! http://bit.ly/broomescholarships

💵 What do you need to do to be considered?

It’s easy! Complete your Online Application by answering some questions, writing some short essays, and making sure that you complete any follow-up requirements. The application usually takes students less than an hour to complete.

💵 What do you need to do to boost your chances of earning a scholarship?

Read the essay questions carefully so you know what to write about.

Look professional! Write your essays in something with spell-check (the scholarship system does not have spell-check) and then paste your essay into the application.

Best of luck with your application! Have a question or need help? Contact us at foundation@sunybroome.edu

Graduate Together: America Honors the High School Class of 2020, a one-hour primetime show paying tribute to high school seniors, their teachers, and families will air Saturday, May 16, at 8 p.m. This commercial-free special will air on ABC, CBS, FOX, and NBC, and it will also be available through Complex Networks, Facebook, Instagram, PEOPLE, Snapchat, TikTok, and YouTube.

During the show, high school seniors and other viewers will be invited to visit the Graduate Together website (https://www.graduatetogether2020.com/) and click on their state to see specialized content for their graduating class. Students may visit the national Graduate Together website to submit photos, videos, and speeches for a chance to be featured on the show.

Staff from Cornell Cooperative Extension of Broome County handed out sanitizer and masks to farm owners and employees Thursday at Palmer Elementary. Employees each received two masks and an individual bottle of sanitizer. Farm owners received a gallon of sanitizer and two masks for each of their employees.
"All of the farms that are participating interact with the general public. We want people to feel comfortable going to places like farm stands and greenhouses," said Laura Biasillo, Agricultural Economic Development Specialist for CCE of Broome Co.
Farmers can call 772-8953 between 10a-2p to schedule a pickup of masks and sanitizer.

Windsor bus drivers gave a special salute to the senior class Friday, using 22 buses to spell out, "2020" in the Windsor Central High School parking lot.
In addition to spelling out “2020” with buses, the drivers also wrote the names of each Windsor senior between the buses.
“We wanted to show them we care. It’s our way of saying goodbye and letting them know they aren’t forgotten,” said Windsor bus driver Nancy Flanagan. “They grow up with us. They first get on our bus when they’re four years old.”

post_text:
CLASS OF 2020 Photos for Senior DVD

The Memory DVD is created and given to each member of the class of 2020 as part of the graduation packet. The showing of the Class of 2020 video happens during the Senior Banquet scheduled in early June. Each member of the class of 2020 is invited to send in 3 personal photos. Example would be baby, toddler, middle school.

Please send all photos in digital format to mjwardel@windsor-csd.org.
If you have ‘old” prints, take a photo of them with your cell phone and submit them as an attachment in email.

We encourage you to send in lots of group photos. The length of the Senior Video is approximately 25-30 minutes depending on how much participation we have.

In recognition of Memorial Day, the Broome County Legislature would like students to draw, color, or paint a patriotic or veteran-themed picture that can be shared with the community. Once they finalize their piece, they can scan it or take a horizontal photo and email it to LegClerk@broomecounty.us. In addition, people can also submit a photo of their child holding their artwork.
The Legislature would like each photo to include the child’s name, age, grade, school district and a title for their piece. The deadline to submit the artwork is Friday, May 15, 2020.

post_text:
Superintendent's Day isn't just a time for teacher professional development. Windsor CSD bus drivers get training in how to get children off of a smoke-filled bus, emergency care, and extinguishing fire.
The state mandates training on certain topics in the fall. In the spring, the district has more discretion.
"In the spring, I try to be more creative and hands-on. We try to make it fun and interesting, but still something that is a learning opportunity," said bus driver Diane Garlick, who organized the training.
text:
Superintendent's Day isn't just a time for teacher professional development. Windsor CSD bus drivers get training in how to get children off of a smoke-filled bus, emergency care, and extinguishing fire.
The state mandates training on certain topics in the fall. In the spring, the district has more discretion.
"In the spring, I try to be more creative and hands-on. We try to make it fun and interesting, but still something that is a learning opportunity," said bus driver Diane Garlick, who organized the training.

post_text:
Thank you to San Francisco Bay Brand Inc. for gifting 20 Brine Shrimp hatching kits to Mrs. Kocak's class. Student Christian Varelakis wrote a letter to the company and they responded not only with a letter back, but gifts for the class as well.

Students in Mrs. Kocak's class has been writing letters to companies and individuals for several years now as a part of their science fair projects. Each student chooses a person or company to write to about their science fair findings and often the companies write back. The students were extremely excited to receive such a generous response this time and shared with other teachers and classmates.

Christian did an experiment on different salinity levels and the hatching rate of the brine shrimp. He, along with 18 other students, will present their projects at the Southern Tier Scholastic Science Fair March 21. Christian plans on bringing some kits to show the judges and his fellow participants.

Each student chooses a person or company to write to about their science fair findings and often the companies write back. The students were extremely excited to receive such a generous response this time and shared with other teachers and classmates.

Christian did an experiment on different salinity levels and the hatching rate of the brine shrimp. He, along with 18 other students, will present their projects at the Southern Tier Scholastic Science Fair March 21. Christian plans on bringing some kits to show the judges and his fellow participants.

Riley celebrated her 9th birthday on Valentine's day. Her 9-year work anniversary as a therapy dog at Palmer Elementary is in April. She may be 56 in dog years (we googled it), but she's never too old to roam the halls at Palmer.
"Kids enjoyed walks with her (on her birthday) here at Palmer. Then, we spent time at the high school visiting her friends from years past, many whom are now seniors," said her owner Rhonda Ashley.

Here is a site you can use if you would like to learn more about the trail with your advisory! https://www.appalachiantrail.org/home/explore-the-trail

post_text:
Parents and other family members flocked to Weeks Elementary for the first grade writer’s celebration. As a conclusion to the nonfiction writing unit, students presented a finished chapter book to their family members. Throughout the process, students had to write facts they knew about topics of their choice, illustrate each chapter, edit, and design a cover for their finished product.

“The students were so proud to show off their work. When asked what they were most proud of, students replied ‘myself’, ‘my pictures’, and ‘how hard I worked to write 13 chapters in my book,’” said teacher Rachel Bates.
